# As shown above, this training sub-dataset contains simulation results
# of 27 readings(3 operational measurement + 24 sensor readings) from 100 
# jet engines with a max cycle count of 362.
# There are a total number of 20631 entries. 
# To reduce the operation time of the experiment only the sensor 7's reading
# From the first 10 engines are used to validate the performance of GP algorithm

# the dataframe is trimed according to the specification stated in comment above
df = df[df[0] ==1]
df = df.iloc[:,[0,1,7]]

Normalization of the data¶

In [76]:
# It is a good idea to normalize the data first before applying GP Regression becasue
# 1. We cen set mean function to 0 after we normalized the data to simplify computation time
# 2. We are less familar with the exact units working with; different units might result in poor result

x = df.values

min_max_scaler = preprocessing.MinMaxScaler()
x_scaled = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(x)

df_norm = pd.DataFrame(x_scaled)
df_norm[0] = df[0]
df_norm[1] = df[1]

Experiment 1: Filling 25% - 50% - 75% Missing Values¶

In [17]:
# Intentionally drop 25%, 50% or 75% of the missing values
# This is done by randomly droppping the X percentage of the dataframe index 

drop_25_index = df_norm.sample(frac=.25).index
drop_50_index = df_norm.sample(frac=.50).index
drop_75_index = df_norm.sample(frac=.75).index

df_drop_25 = df_norm.drop(drop_25_index)
df_drop_50 = df_norm.drop(drop_50_index)
df_drop_75 = df_norm.drop(drop_75_index)

print('Shape for 25% missing value: {} '.format(df_drop_25.shape))
print('Shape for 50% missing value: {} '.format(df_drop_50.shape))
print('Shape for 75% missing value: {} '.format(df_drop_75.shape))

GP Model Setup¶

In [20]:
# Initialize the covariance function(i.e. Kernel function) and the mean function

with pm.Model() as model:
    
    # Initialize the piror (i.e inital hyper-parameters) for the kernel function 
     = pm.Gamma("", alpha=2, beta=1)
    
    # The Half Cauchy distribution is selected and used instead of the standard normal distribution
    # Compared to normal distribution Cauchu distribition has a longer tails 
    # The sensor readings might contain outliers that are very large/small
    # Thus Cauchy distribution is used here
     = pm.HalfCauchy("", beta=5)

    cov = **2 * pm.gp.cov.Matern52(1, )
    gp = pm.gp.Marginal(cov_func=cov)

     = pm.HalfCauchy("", beta=5)
    y_ = gp.marginal_likelihood("y", X=np.array(df_drop_25[df_drop_25[0]==1].index).reshape(-1,1),\
                                y=df_drop_25[df_drop_25[0]==1][2].values, noise=)

    # Use the built in function to calculate the maximum a posterier propbability
    mp = pm.find_MAP()
100.00% [19/19 00:00<00:00 logp = 13.997, ||grad|| = 25.732]

# New values from x=0 to x=200
X_new = np.linspace(0, 200, 200)[:,None]

# Add the GP conditional to the model, given the new X values
with model:
    f_pred = gp.conditional("f_pred", X_new)

# To use the MAP values, you can just replace the trace with a length-1 list with `mp`
with model:
    pred_samples = pm.sample_posterior_predictive([mp], vars=[f_pred], samples=2000)

    y_samples["y_pred"][average_50_rmse_index,:].T[local_index] = local_measurement
    
    
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,5)); ax = fig.gca()

# posterior predictive distribution
plot_gp_dist(ax, y_samples["y_pred"],X_new, plot_samples=False, palette="bone_r");

# overlay a scatter of one draw of random points from the
#   posterior predictive distribution
plt.plot(X_new, y_samples["y_pred"][average_50_rmse_index, :].T, "o-", ms=2, label="Predicted data");

# plot original data and true function

Accuracy for 75 Percent Missing Values¶












In [43]:



    


# Initialize the covariance function(i.e. Kernel function) and the mean function

with pm.Model() as model:
    
    # Initialize the piror (i.e inital hyper-parameters) for the kernel function 
     = pm.Gamma("", alpha=2, beta=1)
    
    # The Half Cauchy distribution is selected and used instead of the standard normal distribution
    # Compared to normal distribution Cauchu distribition has a longer tails 
    # The sensor readings might contain outliers that are very large/small
    # Thus Cauchy distribution is used here
     = pm.HalfCauchy("", beta=5)

    cov = **2 * pm.gp.cov.Matern52(1, )
    gp = pm.gp.Marginal(cov_func=cov)

     = pm.HalfCauchy("", beta=5)
    y_ = gp.marginal_likelihood("y", X=np.array(df_drop_75[df_drop_75[0]==1].index).reshape(-1,1),\
                                y=df_drop_75[df_drop_75[0]==1][2].values, noise=)

    # Use the built in function to calculate the maximum a posterier propbability
    mp = pm.find_MAP()
